  1. Make a labeled histogram (with 30 bins) of the ages of the houses in the data set, and describe the distribution.
ames_train$age <- 2010-ames_train$Year.Built
hist(ames_train$age, xlab = "Years")

The distribution is strongly shifted to the right. The bar graph shows us that many new houses have been built recently. The location seems to be multimodal with its peak around buildings 30-50 years old, and the oldest house is about 140 years old.

  1. The mantra in real estate is Location, Location, Location! Make a graphical display that relates a home price to its neighborhood in Ames, Iowa. Which summary statistics are most appropriate to use for determining the most expensive, least expensive, and most heterogeneous (having the most variation in housing price) neighborhoods? Report which neighborhoods these are based on the summary statistics of your choice. Report the value of your chosen summary statistics for these neighborhoods.

  1. We want to predict the natural log of the home prices. Candidate explanatory variables are lot size in square feet (Lot.Area), slope of property (Land.Slope), original construction date (Year.Built), remodel date (Year.Remod.Add), and the number of bedrooms above grade (Bedroom.AbvGr). Pick a model selection or model averaging method covered in the Specialization, and describe how this method works. Then, use this method to find the best multiple regression model for predicting the natural log of the home prices.
fit_lm = lm(log(price) ~ Lot.Area + Land.Slope + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + Bedroom.AbvGr, 
            data = ames_train)
summary(fit_lm)

fit_bic = bas.lm(log(price) ~ Lot.Area + Land.Slope + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + Bedroom.AbvGr, 
                 data = ames_train,
                 prior = "BIC",
                 modelprior = uniform(),
                 method = "MCMC" )
summary(fit_bic)

A way to work around the problem with choosing the right model is to implement Bayesian model averaging (BMA), in which several models are averaged to produce posterior coefficient values and predictions based on new data. For the model, pre-distribution is selected and BIC is selected as the pre-distribution. To calculate the probability of the model, we use the Markov Monte Carlo chain. (MCMC) In addition, BIC chooses simpler models than AIC. Thus, from the current BMA (BIC and MCMC), we can see that the model proposes to keep all the variables as the most appropriate predictors of house prices.

  1. Which home has the largest squared residual in the previous analysis (Question 4)? Looking at all the variables in the data set, can you explain why this home stands out from the rest (what factors contribute to the high squared residual and why are those factors relevant)?
plot(fit_bic)

ames_train$res_sqr <- fit_lm$residuals**2
which(ames_train$res_sqr == max(ames_train$res_sqr))
## 428 
## 428
exp(fit_lm$fitted.values[428])
##      428 
## 103176.2

By comparing the residuals on the plot, we found that house # 428 (PID 902207130) looks like an outlier, which tells us that it has the largest squared residual. The chart shows that the lot does not fit the model. This can be explained by the lowest price of the house and the year it was built. It sold for just over $ 12,000. The target price is $ 103,176.20 making it a significant variance. It has an unfinished basement and was sold in abnormal conditions. Both variables are not included in our model. This seems to be the most likely explanation for the low selling price.

  1. Do you think it is better to log transform Lot.Area, in terms of assumptions for linear regression? Make graphs of the predicted values of log home price versus the true values of log home price for the regression models selected for Lot.Area and log(Lot.Area). Referencing these two plots, provide a written support that includes a quantitative justification for your answer in the first part of question 7.
plot(ames_train$price~fit_lm$fitted.values)
abline(lm(ames_train$price~fit_lm$fitted.values), col="red")

plot(log(ames_train$price)~fit_lm_log$fitted.values)
abline(lm(log(ames_train$price)~fit_lm_log$fitted.values), col="red")

According to these graphs, you can see that it is better to log the Lot.Area transformation, because after the log transformation the data looks more linear. And it is clear from the model summary that the log transformation results in a larger R-squared value.
